    "justification": "Five conjuncts encode the sign-flip claim: (1)+(2) opposite signs (positive for CO, negative for NCO) — the central observation; (3)+(4) both magnitudes substantively above noise floor (|partial r| > 0.1) so the sign flip is not a near-zero coin flip; (5) Steiger Z p < 0.01 confirms the difference between CO and NCO partial correlations is statistically meaningful (not a coincidence of small differences).",
    "failure_mode": "If either partial r changed sign, or if both fell below |0.1|, or if Steiger p > 0.01, the sign-flip mechanism claim collapses to either 'same direction in both' (refutes mechanistic distinction between CO and NCO resolution) or 'too small to distinguish' (insufficient power)."
  },
  "conclusion": {
    "assertion": "After GC residualization, mean groove width has a positive partial Spearman correlation with crossover rate (+0.218) and an opposite-signed correlation with non-crossover rate (-0.202) at 1 Mb autosomal resolution; the difference is significant by Steiger's Z test for dependent correlations (p < 1e-6). Wider major-groove geometry promotes crossover resolution while disfavoring non-crossover resolution, consistent with mechanically distinct strand-invasion / Holliday-junction physics for the two outcomes.",
    "formal": null,
